title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant Stock 91/30 M44 Refinish
postcontent:
This auction is for SERVICE and NOT for any physical goods

I offer the service of completely stripping the old finish from your Mosin rifle stock and returning it to you in bare wood condition ready for you to apply new finish.


Here is how it works:
1.	You give me your old Mosin stock (metal end caps can stay)
2.	I strip old finish (aka varnish)
3.	I sand wooden stock until it’s smooth to touch and ready to accept new finish (stain, oil, etc.). It will appear just the way Mother Nature (with comrade’s Stalin approval) meant it to be.
4.	You will apply the final finish – oil, stain, varnish, burn with torch, engrave, carve – wherever your fantasy takes you.

The pictures below will give you an idea of what you will get back. This is my current project. I added a picture at the end of what your stock would look like with (5) coats of oil or some type of clear coat. The easiest way to “predict” new look is to get the wood wet with a damp cloth. I can only upload 3 pictures so if you need to see more I can email. 

COST: You pay $50 for my work.

I think anyone who ever refinished wood knows how long it takes to strip and sand/polish it. And then sand it again, and again, and again… Not to mention cost of chemicals and other materials. 

ADDITIONAL SERVICE: For extra $30 I will apply oil or stain of your choice. One condition – you will have to tell me a specific name of the stain you want me to use and I will buy it from Home Depot or Lowe’s. Stores have a decent verity of Minwax stains like mahogany, oak, red oak, gunstock, etc. The reason here is I’ve seen it too many times when people envision one thing and then it looks a bit different after stain dries. This way I am not responsible for color because I did want you told me to do. 

BE AWARE: Attached pictures represent a typical Mosin stock. However, Russians used various types of wood in their production and therefore your stock may be lighter or darker. Occasionally I find repairs/patches after I strip darker tone varnish on old stocks that were not very visible before. You can hide them again with darker stain but not with clear coat or oil.

Dings, dents, deep scratches, cracks will still be there after I strip your stock. You can try to fill them prior to staining but that’s something for you to do. 

LEAD TIME: 1-3 weeks. Depends on services you order, number of ongoing orders, weather, and my availability. 

                         --- Turn that old and flaky stock into a beauty ---

Reply to this add or text me at 77O_six five six_89two5

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1886
postcontent: Winchester 1886 marked 45/90 but I think it was rechambered to 45/70. I dont have a 45/90 to check it but it shoots 45/70's great. Very accurate for a rifle made in 1895 (S/N 908xx). Stock has been refinished and is a little low in spots. The barrel is 21" and has been shortened as far as I can tell. The rifle did have a full size mag at one time as there is a grove on the bottom of the barrel. I have shot this rifle plenty and it out shoots every 1886 I have seen. Bore is an 8+ with some shine and sharp groves. Beautiful red color in the stock. Was probably case hardened when new but looks like blue was applied a long time ago. Lettering is still sharp and clear. I am cuting my winchesters back a little and you wont find a better deal on a 1886 antique than this one

title: For Sale:  Brand New Remington 770 .270 rifle with bushnell scope
postcontent:
This is a brand new rifle with only 10 rounds shot down the pipe.  I bought it, shot it once, cleaned it, and then left it in the safe, (thought I'd get to hunt this year, but I didn't), so it hasn't got a scratch on it.  I also haven't had it too long.

It comes with Bushnell scope, which I sighted in with a laser at about 50 yards. So it's true right and left, but may need a little tweaking if you want to zero it in at 100 or 200. Comes with the remaining 10 rounds I haven't shot (I'm also including old spent brass as well). Also comes with a black soft gun case.

This gun bolt has the three lugs like the TC venture, which I really like.  It has a smooth action, and the bolt doesn't have to rise up a lot in reloading, which is nice with a scope on it.

Also has a very thick rubber butt pad, which helps a lot. I felt very little kick when I fired it.

In spite of the not so nice reviews about this model, this is a really good shooting rifle.  Below I'll leave a link to a guy shooting one of these, and you can see for yourself if they are not awesome rifles...

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_e7ILmiLtsw

title: For Sale:  Winchester 1886 45/70
postcontent: Winchester 1886 marked 45/70 but I think it was rechambered to 45/70. I dont have a 45/90 to check it but it shoots 45/70's great. Very accurate for a rifle made in 1895 (S/N 908xx). Stock has been refinished and is a little low in spots. The barrel is 21" and has been shortened as far as I can tell. The rifle did have a full size mag at one time as there is a grove on the bottom of the barrel. I have shot this rifle plenty and it out shoots every 1886 I have seen. Bore is an 8+ with some shine and sharp groves. Beautiful red color in the stock. Was probably case hardened when new but looks like blue was applied a long time ago. Lettering is still sharp and clear. I am cuting my winchesters back a little and you wont find a better deal on a 1886 antique than this one
